==English==
===Etymology===
From Latin ''dominium'' through Middle English ''daunger'' and Anglo-French ''dangier''

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|ˈdeɪndʒɝ}} (''US'')
*{{audio|en-us-danger.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# ''(Obsolete):'' Power to harm; subjection or liability to penalty. See In one's danger, below.
#:''"You stand within his '''danger''', do you not?" (Shakespeare, ''Merchant of Venice'', 4:1)''
#:''"Covetousness of gains hath brought [them] in '''danger''' of this statute" (More, ''Utopia'').''
# Exposure to injury, loss, pain, or other evil; peril; risk; insecurity.
# ''(Obsolete):'' Difficulty; sparingness.
# ''(Obsolete):'' Coyness; disdainful behavior.
# ''(Obsolete):'' A place where one is in the hands of the enemy.
# Exposure to liable harm.
#:''"Danger is a good teacher, and makes apt scholars" (Hazlitt, ''Table talk'').''

